05059nam a22006615i 9780774867450DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748674507 a10.59962/97807748674502doi  a(DE-B1597)661392  a(OCoLC)1284980953  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKIC5532.7b.R83 2021 7aLAW1100002bisacsh04a346.71404/32089972231 aRück, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Laws and the Land :bThe Settler Colonial Invasion of Kahnawà:ke in Nineteenth-Century Canada /cDaniel Rück. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (336 p.) :b27 b&w photos, 5 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLaw and Society00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tKahnawà:ke and Canada -- t“Whereas the Seigniory of Sault St. Louis Is the Property of the Iroquois Nation” -- t“Out of the Beaten Track” -- t“In What Legal Anarchy Will Questions of Property Soon Find The mselves” -- t“The Consequences of This Promiscuous Ownership” -- t“Equal to an Ordnance Map of the Old Country” -- t“It Is Necessary to Follow the Custom of the Reserve Which Is Contrary to Law” -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tPublications of the Osgoode Society for Canadian Legal History0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs the settler state of Canada expanded into Indigenous lands, settlers dispossessed Indigenous people and undermined their sovereignty as nations. One site of invasion was Kahnawà:ke, a Kanien’kehá:ka community and part of the Rotinonhsiónni confederacy. The Laws and the Land delineates the establishment of a settler colonial relationship from early contact ways of sharing land; land practices under Kahnawà:ke law; the establishment of modern Kahnawà:ke in the context of French imperial claims; intensifying colonial invasions under British rule; and ultimately the Canadian invasion in the guise of the Indian Act, private property, and coercive pressure to assimilate. What Daniel Rück describes is an invasion spearheaded by bureaucrats, Indian agents, politicians, surveyors, and entrepreneurs. This original, meticulously researched book is deeply connected to larger issues of human relations with environments, communal and individual ways of relating to land, legal pluralism, historical racism and inequality, and Indigenous resurgence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFirst NationsxLegal status, laws, etczQuébec (Province)zKahnawake. 0aFirst NationszQuébec (Province)zKahnawakexGovernment relations. 0aIndians of North AmericaxLegal status, laws, etc.zQuébec (Province)zKahnawake. 0aIndians of North AmericazQuébec (Province)zKahnawakexGovernment relations. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLand tenurezQuébec (Province)zKahnawake. 0aLand tenurexLaw and legislationzQuébec (Province)zKahnawake Indian ReserveexHistoryy19th century2DLC. 0aLand tenurezQuébec (Province)zKahnawakexHistory. 0aMohawk IndiansxLand tenurezQuébec (Province)zKahnawake Indian ReservexHistoryy19th century2DLC. 0aSettler colonialismzCanada. 0aSettler colonialismzQuébec (Province)zKahnawake Indian ReservexHistoryy19th century2DLC. 7aLAW / Indigenous Peoples.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311141764640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077